Some Chinese students studying abroad are affected by the epidemic. What should they do if their studies are blocked? The Department of Education has responded.

According to Xinhua News Agency, on February 12, Wang Dengfeng, director of the Office of the Ministry of Education's Leading Group for the response to the new pneumonia epidemic, said at a news conference of the Joint Prevention and control mechanism of the State Council, in view of the fact that some overseas students are unable to study in foreign institutions on time, the Ministry of Education instructs the embassies, consulates and educational departments stationed abroad to actively communicate and coordinate with the educational departments and universities stationed abroad, urge the foreign party to make good arrangements for my students studying abroad.

"We will provide effective learning assistance by extending the enrollment time, online courses, flexible arrangements for graduation defense, and at the same time solve the problem of visa extension for our overseas students as soon as possible to minimize the negative impact of the entry restriction measures and protect the legitimate rights and interests of our overseas students, " Wang said, at present, with the promotion of our embassies and consulates abroad, some countries have introduced measures to help solve the academic problems encountered by Chinese students studying abroad.

As of February 13, the outbreak had spread to 25 countries, including China. Who has repeatedly stressed the importance of refraining from restrictions that are inconsistent with the IHR, such as restrictions on movement and trade.

A reporter from the HSINKING newspaper chatted with several Chinese students and listened to their stories about what happened during the epidemic.

━━━━━

"As Hubei People, self-isolation is our duty. "

Gigi, a native of Hubei Province, has been staying at home since returning home from a graduate school in Canberra, The Australian capital, for the Spring Festival. He was supposed to be on his way back to school by now, but the outbreak threw everything into disarray.

In response to the risk of a new outbreak of pneumonia, the Australian government has decided that from February 1, all non-australian citizens leaving or transiting from mainland China will not be allowed to enter the country for 14 days, according to a statement on the website of the Chinese Embassy in Australia.

"Now I have to stay at home, and it's better to stick to the national arrangement of self-isolation, " said Gigi, who was contacted by Australian schools offering "online classes" and other solutions. Online courses for some professional students, can save time, keep up with the pace of learning, is a good suggestion. However, there are practical problems, such as how to complete the group work, the mid-term examination in the absence of school how to carry out.

When asked if he had considered returning to Australia earlier, "As a native of Hubei, it is my due awareness and responsibility to isolate myself for at least 14 days, " Gigi said. The quarantine period is not yet over in January, and if you return to Australia early, you will not only risk infection, but if you get the stigma of 'going abroad with a disease' , you will also have a negative impact on the image of Chinese students, which will not be worth the loss. "

But he also has concerns about his education, which may need to be extended into the second semester of the year if he is unable to attend for long periods and his visa may need to be renewed. He hopes to be able to get accurate information from the official as soon as possible, to determine when, through what means to return to school to continue their studies.

"there are no masks on the market. Students and teachers ask about it. "

Molly, who is a doctoral student at the Hokkaido University in Japan, has recently seen a rise in the number of confirmed cases on the diamond princess on television, as well as a rise in the number of students wearing face masks on campus.

From the end of January, the school began to send students about the epidemic of new pneumonia, including travel alerts, overseas relatives visit Japan, personal hygiene measures to prevent virus infection. Ms. Mo said that recent Japanese classmates and mentors had been asking her about the outbreak in China. "They were totally concerned, asking if my family was okay, how Wuhan was doing, and so on. "

Referring to the large number of medical supplies sent by Japan to support China, Molly said masks were no longer available in her region, and occasionally a few went on the shelves, but were quickly snapped up. At the moment, no-wash alcohol is completely out of stock. In this case, the Japanese are still sending a large number of domestic supplies to various regions of China for support, is really quite moved.

According to the Chinese Embassy in Japan, since the outbreak of the new pneumonia in China, the central and local governments and various sectors of society in Japan have expressed condolences to China and actively donated money and materials. As of February 7, more than 6.338 million masks, more than 1.047 million pairs of gloves, protective clothing, protective clothing, protective clothing, goggles, thermometers, disinfection water and so on have been donated by various circles in Japan, with a total donation of about 30.602 million yuan.

"An all-you-can-go vacation"

Kobayashi flew to Thailand on Feb. 11 and booked a bed and breakfast at Airbnb for a 14 day indoor vacation.

In fact, he should have returned to the University of San Francisco in early February, but affected by the outbreak, at home waiting for a week, the provisional decision to go to a "third country" isolation for 14 days, in Thailand Transit.

Kobayashi said that in previous discussions with the school, the program offered was not very satisfactory. "It's really a quick vacation, Thailand is a nice place and the locals are friendly. But for safety, I decided to stay at a bed-and-breakfast, " he said, i wasn't sure if I'd make it back to school after 14 days in Thailand, but I wanted to give it a try.

The web site of the Chinese Consulate General in San Francisco released the news on February 6, reminding Chinese citizens to pay attention to the changes in local entry and exit policies when transiting through a third place. It is recommended to visit the web site of the Chinese Embassy and consulate in the United States and the Chinese consular service website, keep up to date.

Kobayashi told reporters he hoped that other students with academic difficulties would complain less and complain less, have more confidence and avoid creating panic on social networks.

"Let me give you a hug. "

ESCARGOT, a student at the University of Edinburgh in the UK, said she had bought a mask but had not worn it outside. "I feel like I have to be sick here to wear a mask, " she said. "there is no new pneumonia in Scotland and very few people wear masks. "

The Chinese Embassy in the UK issued a notice on its website on February 3, "since the confirmation of the case in the UK, there has been an increase in public concern about the outbreak, with insults, discriminatory remarks and even violence directed at Chinese students and overseas Chinese in some areas. The Chinese Embassy in the UK has reminded Chinese citizens in the UK to properly respond to the provocation of undesirable elements."

Regarding the embassy's announcement, snail king said that he had heard of "discrimination" in some British cities. The University of Edinburgh had sent an email to students, stressing that they should not be treated differently because of the epidemic, if Chinese students encounter adverse incidents such as discrimination, they can contact the staff at any time to deal with them.

In addition, she shared a heartwarming story about a friend. On their way to a supermarket, Chinese students at a University of Glasgow in Scotland were asked by a local grandmother, "are you a Chinese student? " When they answered "Yes. " She said, "let me give you a hug, " and she hugged them and said, "welcome to Scotland. ".

Zhao Lin, editor, Hsinking Daily News
